## Overview

Choose and implement the typography system that will define the luxury feel of the application. Serif fonts convey elegance and tradition, while sans-serif provides clean readability.

## Types

```typescript
interface TypographySystem {
  fontSerifFamily: string;     // Headline font
  fontSansFamily: string;      // Body font
  fontSizeH1: string;          // 2.5rem
  fontSizeH2: string;          // 2rem
  fontSizeBody: string;        // 1rem
  lineHeightTight: number;     // 1.2
  lineHeightNormal: number;    // 1.5
  letterSpacingTight: string;  // 0px
  letterSpacingWide: string;   // 0.05em
}
```

## Implementation Guide

### Step 1: Select fonts

**Recommended combinations:**
- Playfair Display (serif) + Inter (sans-serif)
- Georgia (serif) + Poppins (sans-serif)
- Cormorant Garamond (serif) + Inter (sans-serif)

### Step 2: Load fonts

**Files:** `src/styles/typography.css` or `public/index.html`

```css
/* src/styles/typography.css */
@import url('https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Playfair+Display:wght@400;700&family=Inter:wght@400;500;600;700&display=swap');

:root {
  --font-serif: 'Playfair Display', serif;
  --font-sans: 'Inter', sans-serif;
  --font-size-h1: 2.5rem;
  --font-size-h2: 2rem;
  --font-size-h3: 1.75rem;
  --font-size-body: 1rem;
  --font-size-caption: 0.875rem;
  --line-height-tight: 1.2;
  --line-height-normal: 1.5;
  --letter-spacing-tight: 0px;
  --letter-spacing-wide: 0.05em;
}

h1, h2, h3 { 
  font-family: var(--font-serif); 
  line-height: var(--line-height-tight);
}

body { 
  font-family: var(--font-sans);
  line-height: var(--line-height-normal);
}
```

### Step 3: Define hierarchy

Create consistent heading and text styles across the app.

## Design Decisions

### Why Playfair Display vs Georgia?

1. **Playfair Display**: More distinctive, luxury feel, designed for web
2. **Georgia**: System font, faster load, more conservative

Recommend Playfair for the premium feel, with Georgia as fallback.

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] Serif font selected for headlines (Georgia, Playfair Display, or similar)
- [ ] Sans-serif font selected for body (Inter, Poppins, or similar)
- [ ] Fonts loaded via Google Fonts or self-hosted
- [ ] Font stack configured in CSS
- [ ] Font hierarchy defined (h1-h6, body, labels, captions)

## References

- Google Fonts: https://fonts.google.com
- Related file: `src/styles/colors.css` (use together)

## Overview

Design tokens are the single source of truth for design decisions. They ensure consistency and make global changes easy. This ticket establishes spacing, shadows, borders, and transitions.

## Types

```typescript
interface DesignTokens {
  // Spacing (8px base)
  space1: string;  // 0.5rem = 8px
  space2: string;  // 1rem = 16px
  space3: string;  // 1.5rem = 24px
  space4: string;  // 2rem = 32px
  space5: string;  // 3rem = 48px
  space6: string;  // 4rem = 64px

  // Shadows
  shadowSm: string;
  shadowMd: string;
  shadowLg: string;

  // Border Radius
  radiusSm: string;  // 8px
  radiusMd: string;  // 12px
  radiusLg: string;  // 16px

  // Transitions
  transitionFast: string;  // 150ms
  transitionBase: string;  // 300ms
  transitionSlow: string;  // 500ms
}
```

## Implementation Guide

### Step 1: Create tokens file

**Files:** `src/styles/tokens.css`

```css
/* src/styles/tokens.css */
:root {
  /* Spacing Scale (8px base) */
  --space-1: 0.5rem;    /* 8px */
  --space-2: 1rem;      /* 16px */
  --space-3: 1.5rem;    /* 24px */
  --space-4: 2rem;      /* 32px */
  --space-5: 3rem;      /* 48px */
  --space-6: 4rem;      /* 64px */

  /* Shadows */
  --shadow-sm: 0 1px 2px rgba(0,0,0,0.05);
  --shadow-md: 0 4px 6px rgba(0,0,0,0.07);
  --shadow-lg: 0 10px 15px rgba(0,0,0,0.10);

  /* Border Radius */
  --radius-sm: 8px;
  --radius-md: 12px;
  --radius-lg: 16px;

  /* Transitions */
  --transition-fast: 150ms ease;
  --transition-base: 300ms ease;
  --transition-slow: 500ms ease;
}
```

### Step 2: Import in main CSS

**Files:** `src/index.css` or `src/App.css`

```css
@import './styles/colors.css';
@import './styles/typography.css';
@import './styles/tokens.css';
```

### Step 3: Use tokens everywhere

Never hardcode values - always reference tokens:
```css
/* Good */
.card {
  padding: var(--space-3);
  border-radius: var(--radius-md);
  box-shadow: var(--shadow-md);
}

/* Bad */
.card {
  padding: 24px;
  border-radius: 12px;
  box-shadow: 0 4px 6px rgba(0,0,0,0.07);
}
```

## Design Decisions

### Why 8px base spacing?

1. **Mathematical harmony**: 8, 16, 24, 32, 48, 64 form a consistent scale
2. **Responsive friendly**: Easily divisible for different screen sizes
3. **Industry standard**: Used by Material Design, Apple HIG, many design systems

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] Spacing scale (8px base unit) defined: 8, 16, 24, 32, 48, 64px
- [ ] Shadow system defined (subtle elevation levels)
- [ ] Border radius standardized: 12px default
- [ ] All tokens in CSS custom properties
- [ ] File created at `src/styles/tokens.css`

## References

- Depends on: Ticket 1.1 (colors), Ticket 1.2 (typography)
- Material Design spacing: https://material.io/design/layout/spacing-methods.html

## Overview

Buttons are a fundamental interaction element. The luxury redesign requires buttons that feel premium - generous padding, smooth transitions, and clear states.

## Types

```typescript
interface ButtonProps {
  variant: 'primary' | 'secondary' | 'tertiary';
  size?: 'small' | 'medium' | 'large';
  disabled?: boolean;
  onClick?: () => void;
  children: React.ReactNode;
}
```

## Implementation Guide

### Step 1: Create Button component

**Files:** `src/components/Button.jsx`

```jsx
import './Button.css';

export function Button({ variant = 'primary', size = 'medium', disabled, onClick, children }) {
  return (
    <button 
      className={`btn btn--${variant} btn--${size}`}
      disabled={disabled}
      onClick={onClick}
    >
      {children}
    </button>
  );
}
```

### Step 2: Style with design tokens

**Files:** `src/components/Button.css`

```css
.btn {
  font-family: var(--font-sans);
  font-weight: 600;
  border-radius: var(--radius-md);
  transition: var(--transition-base);
  cursor: pointer;
  border: none;
}

.btn--primary {
  background: var(--color-accent-gold);
  color: white;
  padding: var(--space-2) var(--space-4);
}

.btn--primary:hover:not(:disabled) {
  box-shadow: var(--shadow-md);
  transform: translateY(-1px);
}

.btn--secondary {
  background: transparent;
  color: var(--color-secondary-neutral);
  border: 2px solid var(--color-border-subtle);
  padding: var(--space-2) var(--space-4);
}

.btn--tertiary {
  background: transparent;
  color: var(--color-secondary-neutral);
  padding: var(--space-2) var(--space-3);
}

.btn:disabled {
  opacity: 0.5;
  cursor: not-allowed;
}
```

## Design Decisions

### Why three button variants?

1. **Primary**: Main actions (Submit, Add to Plan)
2. **Secondary**: Alternative actions (Cancel, Go Back)
3. **Tertiary**: Subtle actions (Learn More, See Details)

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] Primary button style created (solid, refined)
- [ ] Secondary button style created (outlined)
- [ ] Tertiary button style created (ghost)
- [ ] All states working: hover, active, disabled, focus
- [ ] Component at `src/components/Button.jsx`
- [ ] Uses design tokens

## References

- Depends on: Tickets 1.1, 1.2, 1.3 (design system)
- Follow pattern: See CLAUDE.md for component structure

## Overview

Cards are used throughout the app to display recipes. They need consistent structure, elegant spacing, and proper image handling.

## Types

```typescript
interface CardProps {
  image?: string;
  title: string;
  subtitle?: string;
  actions?: React.ReactNode;
  onClick?: () => void;
  children?: React.ReactNode;
}
```

## Implementation Guide

### Step 1: Create Card component structure

**Files:** `src/components/Card.jsx`

```jsx
import './Card.css';

export function Card({ image, title, subtitle, actions, onClick, children }) {
  return (
    <div className="card" onClick={onClick}>
      {image && (
        <div className="card__image">
          <img src={image} alt={title} loading="lazy" />
        </div>
      )}
      <div className="card__content">
        <h3 className="card__title">{title}</h3>
        {subtitle && <p className="card__subtitle">{subtitle}</p>}
        {children}
      </div>
      {actions && <div className="card__actions">{actions}</div>}
    </div>
  );
}
```

### Step 2: Style with tokens

**Files:** `src/components/Card.css`

```css
.card {
  background: white;
  border-radius: var(--radius-md);
  box-shadow: var(--shadow-sm);
  overflow: hidden;
  transition: var(--transition-base);
}

.card:hover {
  box-shadow: var(--shadow-md);
  transform: translateY(-2px);
}

.card__image {
  width: 100%;
  aspect-ratio: 4/3;
  overflow: hidden;
}

.card__image img {
  width: 100%;
  height: 100%;
  object-fit: cover;
}

.card__content {
  padding: var(--space-3);
}

.card__title {
  font-family: var(--font-serif);
  font-size: var(--font-size-h3);
  margin-bottom: var(--space-1);
}

.card__actions {
  padding: var(--space-2) var(--space-3);
  border-top: 1px solid var(--color-border-subtle);
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] Card layout component created
- [ ] Image area with consistent aspect ratio
- [ ] Content area with proper padding
- [ ] Optional actions area with button slots
- [ ] Shadow applied using design tokens
- [ ] Border radius at 12px
- [ ] Component at `src/components/Card.jsx`

## References

- Depends on: Epic 1 (design system)
- Used in: Discover, Liked, Planner, Detail pages

## Overview

Forms and inputs should feel refined and accessible. Clear focus states, proper labels, and elegant error handling are essential.

## Types

```typescript
interface FormInputProps {
  id: string;
  label: string;
  type?: 'text' | 'email' | 'password' | 'number';
  value: string;
  onChange: (value: string) => void;
  error?: string;
  placeholder?: string;
  required?: boolean;
}
```

## Implementation Guide

### Step 1: Create FormInput component

**Files:** `src/components/FormInput.jsx`

```jsx
import './FormInput.css';

export function FormInput({ id, label, type = 'text', value, onChange, error, placeholder, required }) {
  return (
    <div className="form-input">
      <label htmlFor={id} className="form-input__label">
        {label}
        {required && <span className="form-input__required">*</span>}
      </label>
      <input
        id={id}
        type={type}
        value={value}
        onChange={(e) => onChange(e.target.value)}
        placeholder={placeholder}
        className={`form-input__field ${error ? 'form-input__field--error' : ''}`}
        aria-invalid={!!error}
        aria-describedby={error ? `${id}-error` : undefined}
      />
      {error && (
        <span id={`${id}-error`} className="form-input__error">
          {error}
        </span>
      )}
    </div>
  );
}
```

### Step 2: Style inputs

**Files:** `src/components/FormInput.css`

```css
.form-input {
  margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
}

.form-input__label {
  display: block;
  font-weight: 600;
  margin-bottom: var(--space-1);
  color: var(--color-secondary-neutral);
}

.form-input__field {
  width: 100%;
  padding: var(--space-2);
  border: 2px solid var(--color-border-subtle);
  border-radius: var(--radius-md);
  font-family: var(--font-sans);
  transition: var(--transition-fast);
}

.form-input__field:focus {
  outline: none;
  border-color: var(--color-accent-gold);
  box-shadow: 0 0 0 3px rgba(212, 175, 55, 0.1);
}

.form-input__field--error {
  border-color: #D32F2F;
}

.form-input__error {
  display: block;
  margin-top: var(--space-1);
  color: #D32F2F;
  font-size: var(--font-size-caption);
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] Input field component with elegant styling
- [ ] Label component with typography hierarchy
- [ ] Form wrapper with proper spacing
- [ ] Focus states clear and accessible
- [ ] Error states with subtle red accent
- [ ] Component at `src/components/FormInput.jsx`

## Overview

Tabs organize content elegantly, particularly on the Recipe Detail page. The underline-style design is modern and fits the luxury aesthetic.

## Types

```typescript
interface Tab {
  id: string;
  label: string;
  content: React.ReactNode;
}

interface TabsProps {
  tabs: Tab[];
  defaultTab?: string;
}
```

## Implementation Guide

### Step 1: Build accessible tabs

**Files:** `src/components/Tabs.jsx`

```jsx
import { useState } from 'react';
import './Tabs.css';

export function Tabs({ tabs, defaultTab }) {
  const [activeTab, setActiveTab] = useState(defaultTab || tabs[0]?.id);

  const handleKeyDown = (e, tabId) => {
    if (e.key === 'Enter' || e.key === ' ') {
      e.preventDefault();
      setActiveTab(tabId);
    }
  };

  return (
    <div className="tabs">
      <div className="tabs__list" role="tablist">
        {tabs.map(tab => (
          <button
            key={tab.id}
            role="tab"
            aria-selected={activeTab === tab.id}
            aria-controls={`panel-${tab.id}`}
            id={`tab-${tab.id}`}
            className={`tabs__tab ${activeTab === tab.id ? 'tabs__tab--active' : ''}`}
            onClick={() => setActiveTab(tab.id)}
            onKeyDown={(e) => handleKeyDown(e, tab.id)}
          >
            {tab.label}
          </button>
        ))}
      </div>
      {tabs.map(tab => (
        <div
          key={tab.id}
          role="tabpanel"
          id={`panel-${tab.id}`}
          aria-labelledby={`tab-${tab.id}`}
          hidden={activeTab !== tab.id}
          className="tabs__panel"
        >
          {tab.content}
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
  );
}
```

### Step 2: Style tabs

**Files:** `src/components/Tabs.css`

```css
.tabs__list {
  display: flex;
  gap: var(--space-4);
  border-bottom: 2px solid var(--color-border-subtle);
}

.tabs__tab {
  background: none;
  border: none;
  padding: var(--space-2) 0;
  font-family: var(--font-sans);
  font-weight: 600;
  color: var(--color-secondary-neutral);
  opacity: 0.6;
  cursor: pointer;
  transition: var(--transition-base);
  position: relative;
}

.tabs__tab--active {
  opacity: 1;
}

.tabs__tab--active::after {
  content: '';
  position: absolute;
  bottom: -2px;
  left: 0;
  right: 0;
  height: 2px;
  background: var(--color-accent-gold);
}

.tabs__tab:focus-visible {
  outline: 2px solid var(--color-accent-gold);
  outline-offset: 4px;
}

.tabs__panel {
  padding: var(--space-4) 0;
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] Underline-style tab design implemented
- [ ] Smooth transition between tabs
- [ ] Keyboard navigation working (arrow keys, Enter)
- [ ] Accessible to screen readers
- [ ] Component at `src/components/Tabs.jsx`

## References

- Used in: Recipe Detail page (Epic 6)
- ARIA Tabs Pattern: https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/tabs/

## Overview

Create a responsive grid that displays liked recipes beautifully across all devices.

## Implementation Guide

### Step 1: Build responsive grid

**Files:** `src/pages/LikedPage.jsx`

```css
.liked-grid {
  display: grid;
  gap: var(--space-2);
  max-width: 1200px;
  margin: 0 auto;
  padding: var(--space-3);
}

/* Mobile: 2 columns */
@media (min-width: 320px) {
  .liked-grid {
    grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr);
    gap: var(--space-2); /* 16px */
  }
}

/* Tablet: 3 columns */
@media (min-width: 768px) {
  .liked-grid {
    grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
    gap: var(--space-3); /* 24px */
  }
}

/* Desktop: 4 columns */
@media (min-width: 1024px) {
  .liked-grid {
    grid-template-columns: repeat(4, 1fr);
    gap: var(--space-3); /* 24px */
  }
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] Mobile: 2-column grid with 16px gap
- [ ] Tablet: 3-column grid with 20px gap
- [ ] Desktop: 4-column grid with 24px gap
- [ ] Container max-width 1200px on desktop
- [ ] Padding consistent using tokens
